    <item>
      <title>Gift of Mana, Shaman, and YOU ...</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&amp;message.id=149056#M149056</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;SPAN class=postbody&gt;&lt;FONT size=2&gt;Posted for Chutoi from The Spirit Realm:&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/SPAN&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;SPAN class=postbody&gt;&lt;FONT size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/SPAN&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;SPAN class=postbody&gt;&lt;FONT size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/SPAN&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;SPAN class=postbody&gt;&lt;FONT size=2&gt;To Rashere (or whoever is working on the AAs): &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Can we get some kind of explanation of what is going on with Gift of Mana? I’m sure it’s no great surprise, but you’ve got a lot of very unhappy shaman at the moment (and probably other classes). I understand that the idea was to prevent the firing of GoM on procs and the like, but you’ve managed to completely gut the AA for shaman now that it won't fire on cannibalize. Canna was a spell with a very long recast, for heaven's sake. It was NOT a fast-casting spell. Frankly, things are bad enough with us having Rytan designing our spells, but you’ve managed to gut the only decent thing we got this expansion. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;It’s pretty clear no one up at SoE plays a shaman, we’ve known that for a while. However, please take a look at GoM from our perspective. Let me give you a couple of numbers first— &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;1) We’ve had 2 shaman with full abundant healing and gift of mana cast our direct heal 100 times in their guild hall. One had abundant healing fire 7 times and GoM none. The other had abundant healing fire once. Note, that’s 200 casts of a heal and not one GoM firing. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;2) Shaman spell line-ups are substantially defensive in nature due to our spell lines. Consider, for most shaman, I can name probably 5 of their spells memmed at any one time: malos, canna, slow (turgurs for a great many), our HoT spell, our direct heal spell. A disproportionate percentage of them still mem either spirit of leopard or spirit of panther as well due to the ridiculous resist rates on our DoTs. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Forcing the AA into the heal or harm mentality completely screws our class. We have 20% more mana costs on 95% of our spells anyway since Rytan isn’t bright enough to understand the consequences thereof. Technically, only ONE of the 6 spells most shaman have memorized have a shot at firing GoM—and it’s currently not working on our direct healing. If they have FA or Champion memorized, that falls to one of 7 spells. Shaman have already been firmly relegated into a support class, and now you’ve managed to hose the one bright spot we had—being able to use cannibalize to trigger GoM for nasty spells like Champion to help offset Rytan’s miserable lack of balancing. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Things are not real bright for us this expansion anyway. So far this expansion, we’ve gotten 2 new slows (25% and 40%, both mitigatable, as compared to our normal 75% slows) and a true AE that is a cone instead of a PBAE. Actually, I should say it’s half of a cone (the left half) since as far as I know Rytan hasn’t bothered to fix that spell either. Two of our specialty AAs are advanced rabid bear, which, last I heard, had parsed at 2 dps greater than rabid bear (I have not personally confirmed that, but I can attest that it isn’t very good), and Gift of Mana. Now GoM doesn’t work on 7 of the 9 possible spells many shaman frequently have memorized. Thanks to Rytan’s mana costs and inability to understand relative resist checks, we just don’t DoT that much, and our nukes are small and horribly inefficient. We can’t afford to DoT that much! &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Now we’re being told that having GoM fire on cannibalize was an exploit, and we won’t even be able to get a refund for the AAs after you gutted it’s usefulness. What the heck is going on over there, and can you guys please stop screwing our class over?!? Is there any chance we can get an expansion where our class gets some kind of parity with other classes in terms of upgrade? Just once, out of the last 7 odd expansions, can we please see an expansion where the shaman get some kind of upgrade, or at least hold our own in comparison to other classes?!? Our dps is now lower than ever (no dps increase this expansion), our healing isn’t any better (no upgrade this expansion), our utility isn’t improving . . . &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;We have now dropped substantially behind DoTting classes since necros have been getting DoT upgrades (assuming we could even land what we have thanks to Rytan), our healing is dropping considerably compared to druids thanks to Skin and their more powerful blast heals (and clerics outshine us so far it’s silly—though as healing specialists they should), and we can’t tank much of anything any more, giving lie to the battle priest image. Clerics have better melee abilities, for heaven’s sake, not to mention better mitigation due to armor class changes. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Could you guys please stop screwing us over? We’re already pretty much sucking hind teat on the hog. Either shoot the class or fix it, ffs. At the very least, is there some kind of &amp;lt;gasp&amp;gt; vision for the class? For god’s sake, don’t tell us we’re a slowing class. If you do, I want to see where all of the mobs in every expansion post PoP can mitigate damage from warriors, SKs, paladins, wizards, necros, rogues, rangers, beastlords, berserkers, etc. by 25%, 50%, 75% or just be flat out damage immune. Slow has been substantially nerfed for ages. If that is our primary ability, it’s really time to rethink the class. A lot. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Throw us a bone here! What’s going on?!? &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Chutoi &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;P.S. For all the pundits on the boards around here, yes, this is a rant. It has a purpose though—we’d very much like to know what’s going on.&lt;BR&gt;_________________&lt;BR&gt;Chutoi Doglsobber &lt;BR&gt;70 Shaman of Sol Invictus &lt;BR&gt;The Tribunal&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/SPAN&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
