&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Shaman harm themselves in order to gain mana, which in itself is also a heal (I believe wizards have their Harvest under a Heal category). This is a reduction in HP. The net consequence of a Cannibalise is the loss of HP. The mana gain is not equal to the HP loss. &amp;nbsp;Reduction in HP (net or otherwise) is a harming effect, period. Shaman &lt;STRONG&gt;&lt;U&gt;die&lt;/U&gt;&lt;/STRONG&gt; from Cannibalisation. Death from a spell is a harmful effect, period. &lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Cannibalise is Harmful, period, yet Shaman are able to mitigate the harmful effect by healing themselves. Mitigation of harmful effects are not factored in descriptions otherwise heals would not trigger GoM. &lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Making petty distinctions because you disagree with the interpretation of the plain English description of the AA is rather puerile, even for you.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;The product has changed function without warning, indeed&amp;nbsp;every indication from Beta onward was that Cannibalise's relationship with GoM functioned as described on the tin.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Feedback given in Beta, would have alerted SOE to the fact that the Shaman community considered GoM as a functional entity with Cannibalise and therefore alerted said community to the fact that it was considered an unintended side effect... before the fact... WELL before.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Despite the natural variations in playstyles do not distract against the fact that now the AA does not function as advertised.&amp;nbsp;Since the AA no longer functions as&amp;nbsp;advertised and as precidence&amp;nbsp;a number of&amp;nbsp;any other changes in function, of AA's in the past, people are now entitled to a refund.&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;</description>
